I'm very, very fond of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Neuromancer</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, but it seems clear to me that Gibson's is a lightning that won't strike twice -- <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Count Zero</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Mona Lisa Overdrive</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> seem weak in comparison, as does his more recent work (with the possible exception of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Difference Engine</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->).  There was a script that Gibson wrote for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Neuromancer</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> roughly a decade ago; I picked up a copy when I was in college and was horrifed to discover that he'd ruined his own story.<br>
Johnny Mnemonic (which is from his <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Burning Chrome</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> collection, some of which is actually pretty good) ended up the same way.  It's a cute little story and absolutely horrible as a film, but the film resembles the story only in cosmetic ways -- what is left of the original is such horrifying tidbits as a dolphin named Jones.  I consider Gibson lucky that he was never successful in getting <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Neuromancer</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> made.<br>
One more thing about Johnny Mnemonic -- it has few fans, but one of them is surely Chichester, who I would imagine endless rewatches Henry Rollins's scenes as &quot;Spider&quot;.  Good news for Chi: he's going to be in BAD BOYS II. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=treachery@thesaryrntavern>Treachery</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:green;'>Tavern Patron</span></span><br>  Posts: 129<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(5/16/03 2:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3256.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Erratum</span><hr size=1> Hmm, I was partially mistaken.  I didn't think that Gibson used the word 'matrix' in Neuromancer, but apparently he did:<br>
